Davis                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                               Return to Mercer Street 2001 Table of Contents          by Jordan Davis                   While most pundits of America's social and political discourse are either beating dead horses or tilting at windmills, Patricia J. Williams seeks out the racist, sexist, heterosexist, and classist forces that underlie a number of socio-political pathologies. Williams' regular Nation magazine column, "Diary of a Mad Law Professor" is curious in that it often evokes visceral negativity in casual readers. It certainly affected me that way. At first it was difficult to get beyond the name of her page; thumbing through each issue I sheepishly wondered what this crazy lady would get bent out of shape about this week. Though I generally agreed with her ideas, it struck me that Williams was too radical (as if there really is such a thing in a mainstream media culture that chooses to wear blinders). Williams vigorously uproots conventional wisdom as she strips away the "rich-white-male"-centric viewpoint; power and a voice are given to those who simply are acted upon. Like Howard Zinn who has promoted a view of history through a populist lens, Patricia Williams promotes a viewpoint that examines and judges the treatment of the marginalized.          Williams is clearly not the only contemporary essayist with a broad-minded viewpoint on social issues. Katha Pollitt, E.L. Doctorow, Gore Vidal, and Alexander Cockburn, among many others, are similarly progressive in their opinions on society, politics, and culture. Williams, however, has a modified gestalt upon which her liberal commentary about socio-political affairs is based. The way in which the mechanics of society can be explained is a relationship of dominance and submission, a pornographic association. As described in "Clarence X", pornography, on a level greater than graphic sexuality, is "a habit of thinking that allows self-generated sensation to substitute for interaction with a whole other human being, to substitute for listening or conversing or caring." (123). That which becomes such an object, be it an entire race, class, or identifiable group is transformed into a "malleable 'thing'" upon which to project (123). Pornography's purpose is a blank screen upon which the voyeur's desires are projected; a blank screen upon which "the object becomes interchangeable with the will of the voyeur" (123).          Furthermore, pornography has a clear delineation between those who act and those who are acted upon. In this dichotomy of the active and the passive, dominance and submission are key to serving pornography's purpose. In society the roles of voyeur and "actor" are superimposed: thus dominant groups in society project whatever fears and desires they have onto submissive (read: repressed) groups. To demonstrate such patterns, Williams often exposes what is unconscious and what is taboo-that which we either are unaware of and that which sits in the room like a giant white (black?) elephant that we all try to ignore. Unconscious characterizations of groups become tools upon which the justification of their plight is constructed.          Williams' "Fire and Ice," published in The Alchemy of Race and Rights , explores the tensions (and projections) between the existing and new residents of neighborhoods undergoing gentrification. Manhattan's Noho area during the early 1990s was undergoing social and economic change. As streets like Lafayette and the Bowery had once been refuges for the homeless, their downtown location became desirable for the significantly more affluent. Williams recounts a "neurotic New Yorker" asking her to call the police because, "There are BUMS in the lobby [of her building] again" (134). When Williams explained that she would not call the police on "one old, bent toothless black woman huddled under a yellow blanket with holes in it," the woman became irate, claiming that she was spending "too much goddamned money" to have to deal with those "dangerous" people (134-135). Was an "old, bent toothless black woman" truly "dangerous," or was this a reflex? Certainly, it must be inconvenient to be reminded of one's own role in the plight of America's social underclass through the capitalistic indulgence of gentrification. Economic losers are demonized, and the irrational fear of the homeless perpetuates their plight.          Similarly, negative stereotypes of blacks become intertwined with latent perceptions of ownership, thus reinforcing the racial splintering of New York City. A major example of this thinking is explained in "Teleology on the Rocks." In the wake of the Howard Beach beatings, in which three white teenagers assaulted a group of black men whose car had broken down, Mayor Koch went to the largely black neighborhood of Jamaica to explain the "disgruntlement of residents of Howard Beach" in reference to the interracial protest march that followed the beatings (69). Koch asking them "how they would feel if fourteen hundred white people took to their streets of Jamaica" belies the acceptance of "a remarkable degree of possessiveness about public streets. . .that is racially and not geographically bounded" (69). This ill-fated peace mission by the mayor exposed the attitudes that contribute to a de facto segregation of the City of New York. This undercurrent of supposed racial boundaries was taken advantage of by defense attorneys who claimed that the black men who were walking through the white Howard Beach neighborhood should have stopped at the first available pay phone to get help-they had no business walking into the neighborhood in the first place. The increasing number of affluent whites moving into Harlem, as documented in "Little House in the 'Hood," shows the double standard pertaining to whites moving into traditionally black neighborhoods. Whites are at leisure to move into black neighborhoods, pushing out less affluent minorities-the stable residents that have maintained and fought for improvements in their neighborhood as in Harlem. Howard Beach was a good neighborhood threatened by bad elements; Harlem is a "bad" neighborhood "crying out" for a savior.          Inherent in the relationship of whites and blacks in Howard Beach and Harlem is a projection of stereotypes that serve to polarize "good" and "bad" in the eyes of whites. Blacks are viewed in their stereotypically pathological lifestyles. Why do such feelings exist? Whites project these feelings, these underlying tensions and stereotypes, to make themselves feel more secure. They "know" who the "enemy" is so whenever black men wander into a neighborhood for "no good reason," an appropriate and clear response can immediately be summoned; "those blacks" only bring no good. Whites "know" that the minority neighborhoods they decide to take over are "ghettos" rampant with the dysfunctional black culture of drugs, violence, and broken families. Like European explorers "discovering" the Americas and Africa, these whites view themselves as the tamers of neighborhoods blighted by the poor and lazy, and otherwise inferior. Blacks are thus painted with a broad brush; they become objects of fear and loathing. Stepping away from the distorted lens of such racial pornography, it appears that white fears are indeed hypocritical.          White, straight, Protestant male America's individual phobias are given a collective voice, however, thanks to the media's lens which renders images as accurately as a fun-house mirror. The media's very nature takes public views and crams them into private spaces, be it the television in the living room, the stereo in a taxi, or the tabloid headline screaming from a newsstand. Its influence lies in its universality. Individual fears (dangerous homeless people, violent black men, etc.) are cultivated, harvested, and sold wholesale in a perverted marketplace of ideas. Here the media portrays what dominant societal groups want to see: marginalized groups that embody and affirm their ambitions, their ignorance and their worst fears. Like sexual pornography in which roles of dominance and submission are recreated in visual portrayals and manifestly in real life, this media pornography relays stereotypes that become self-fulfilling prophecies in the physical world. Williams' deconstruction of these forces is done by her appropriation of their own techniques. There is a clear impression of how the media, crackpot and mainstream, maintain and propagate inequality.          Conservative talk radio is certifiably the one media outlet where ill-informed babble is purposefully aimed at projecting fears onto people that become "their property." In "Radio Hoods," Williams characteristically dissects the banter of the AM spectrum by serving up the rhetoric in a bare-bones, slightly-irrational approach, all the while embracing the kernel of absurdity she is cracking: "Is it really just a collapsing economy that spawns this drama of grown people sitting around scaring themselves to death with fantasies of black feminist Mexican able-bodied gay soldiers earning $100,000 a year on welfare who are so criminally depraved. . .?" (47). Williams neatly rolls up many subjects (victims) of hate radio into a neat package that both names victims and at the same time displays stereotypes. In the white, Protestant, straight male world of talk radio, any members of society not in this narrow category are seen as the victimizers of the allegedly endangered white male race. Talk show hosts, with their-quoting the National Review on (King) Rush Limbaugh-"splendidly awful taste" and "delightful offensiveness," use "coded epithets" against the supposed enemy (47, 44). Because the very "megawatted expressions of hate and discrimination" are so nakedly aimed at degradation, Williams does not need to do any doctoring whatsoever. The targets of these rants, onto whom the blame for everything under the sun is pinned, are referred to, in their own words, as "'these people', or 'these minorities' or 'feminazis' or 'liberals' or 'scumbags' or 'pansies' or 'jerks' or 'sleazeballs' or 'loonies' or 'animals' or 'foreigners'" (44). These scapegoats are turned into the property of the listener through degrading labels that wrap these "undesirables" up into a tight package to be batted about at will. Williams also faults the hosts who through "mockery and shouting down of callers. . .roar[s] of incantations, [and] the insistence on agreement," foster culture in which the dominant group is still able to categorize, and thus, dehumanize their supposed enemies (47).          Culture, politics, and the media join together in vivid, pornographic interplay in Williams' "Clarence X" in The Rooster's Egg . In describing the one aspect of pornography associated with controversial Supreme Court Justice Clarence Thomas, Williams uses an extended comparison. She compares Clarence Thomas to Wanda the Wench-comparing an icon of pornographized white racist desires to pornographized male sexual desires. Like female objects in sexual pornography who "enjoy" their dehumanization, Thomas is characterized as "lov[ing] the good old days when a little oppression was good for the soul. . .and taught him the true meaning of community" (124). She finishes with a line whose double entendre is stark: "Affirmative action just emasculates him, and besides blacks should be free to experience the self-help joys of a little bondage" (124). The painful gravity and dark humor of this statement reflects no doubt the irony of a black man who is more conservative on social issues than many conservative white judges. It furthermore paints a subtle picture of an Uncle Tom, perhaps the most pornographized image of American slavery.          Such stark examples will likely be assailed by critics as melodramatic and convoluted, but they drive home the point that Thomas, one of the few blacks in the judiciary with conservative views on par with Justice Scalia, is a symbol of the black man who refuses to step on white peoples' toes. Williams shows that Thomas' attraction was his image as a man who sees nothing wrong with the current state of social and economic inequality: Thomas fit into conservative white desires of a black man who wouldn't speak out, an Uncle Tom or a Mammy. The mainstream press would generally shun such powerful, stinging images, yet this is the essence of Williams' unique wake-up call. Here the underlying cynical racism, in which Thomas plays a role, is unearthed from beneath the heap of political image-making charades by Williams' incisive irreverence.          Comparing Thomas to "Wanda," Williams shows him to be a pacified individual who is rendered malleable by image experts in order to mass-market him. Neo-conservative Justice Thomas was once quoted as calling the 60's Black Nationalist Malcolm X one of his role models. Williams doesn't miss a step in "Clarence X": "Clarence Thomas is to Malcolm X what 'Unforgettable. The perfume. By Revlon' Is to Nat King Cole" (125). This comparison of the sublime and the ridiculous shadows the absurdity of image-making. The humor of such a typical reprimand is tempered by the fact that many blacks did indeed support him. Thomas' mythology was "helpfully concocted by some of the very same public relations people" who marketed George Bush, Ross Perot, Jesse Helms, and Ronald Reagan (125). Williams' scathing criticism of Justice Thomas and his portrayal in the easily-manipulated media was peppered with cutting allusions (in this particular case, an allusion to Ntozake Shange's For Colored Girls Who Have Considered Suicide/When the Rainbow is Enuf ) and readily accessible images. One such example: Justice Thomas was represented "as the product of a land where odds are always overcome, where workers whistle, and where the rainbow is enuf" (126). This marketing of a conservative Thomas as a blend of "Horatio Alger, Miss Jane Pittman and Colin Powell" easily manipulated those in a culture where the media has derelicted its post as watchdog (126). The media allowed itself to be a sort of Wanda the Wench, a body at the service of whatever dominating forces desire it.          With the media acting as a passive Wanda, an intelligent black woman, who intended to make waves and refused to be pacified, was relentlessly attacked for daring to break the boundaries of what others thought she should be. In "A Hearing of One's Own," Williams depicts the ill-fated nomination of Lani Guinier where "she was successfully represented as someone who hated whites and all of Western civilization" (138-139). This was despite the very fact that Guinier is herself the child of an interracial marriage and the third generation of a family of lawyers (138). Guinier was depersonalized; media coverage was not about what she said, but about what she was supposed to have said. There was the "ubiquitous image of Guinier-lips moving, voiceover confirming your worst fears about what she was supposed to have written, what she was supposed to be" (144).          Guinier was branded with the mantle of the "radical black woman," not unlike the outspoken Patricia Williams herself. Because she was not the "typical" black woman riddled with social pathology, she was depicted as "black nationalist" and "irrational feminist" all rolled into one. Society's media has dictated, as was evidenced in the victim bashing during the Tawana Brawley rape trial, that "black women whore as a way of being . . . because it is sensual and lazy and vengeful. How can one be raped?" ("Mirrors and Windows" 175). Furthermore, black women are supposed to be "the bad black mother" ("The Pain of Word Bondage" 163). While blackness invites a series of lurid emotional expectations, being female demands a certain passiveness, like Wanda. Being assertive, intelligent, and persistent draws images of "bitchy, lesbian feminazis," and women who dare to step out of their place, making themselves other than an object for men, draw intense revulsion. The media portrayal and the consequent negative public opinion of Hillary Clinton demonstrated the wrath that punishes a woman daring to abandon her apron for a pantsuit. Lani Guinier thus suffered the double weight of being both a woman and black in the white-male media spotlight.          Consequently, Williams never mentions what Guinier actually said because the entire question of what she really said is moot in light of the fact that she is condemned to history books with words stuck in her mouth by white men who need her to be the irrational, ultra-liberal black woman. She had to wear the crown of thorns as "Quota Queen" ("A Hearing of One's Own, 144-146). Williams' treatment of the "Quota Queen" thus parallels the way in which she was handled by the press. There are abundant quotes from others about what she supposedly said, and there are comparisons of Guinier to the highly-controversial Leonard Jeffries and other Right-wing archetypes of "neo-liberalism," yet there is no discussion or even explanation of her as a person. Though Williams investigates the treatment of Guinier and the underlying motives, Guinier's own ideas are never expressed. Her "supposed" opinions robbed her of a hearing and any possibility of her actually speaking for herself and contradicting the media's anti-Guinier propaganda. Williams herself takes on the role as pornographer for a chapter in order to subtly highlight the workings of Guinier's intellectual rape and her political dehumanization; Guinier just appears as a crazy black lady talking nonsense.          The archetype of the uneducated black person was again echoed in Episode I: The Phantom Menace . One such character, Jar Jar Binks, who speaks "coincidentally" with a Caribbean/West African accent closely associated with African-Americans, is played as "loping", "popeyed", and "brainless" ("Racial Ventriloquism" 9). In the aptly titled "Racial Ventriloquism," Williams criticizes the Amos n'Andy-like portrayals of negative blacks, as well as images that perpetuate the stereotypes of Jews as money-grubbing and soulless. This is perhaps an example of racial pornography at its worst: the creation of fictional characters-aliens-embodying negative stereotypes of today. Williams draws extensively upon the blatant characterizations in both the film and Star Wars Episode I: The Visual Dictionary , and clearly, these characterizations fit into a larger pattern of stereotypes that dehumanize. Is this film, with a large following by children, part of the maintenance of racist institutional thought? Does this film cross the line from a mirror of the inequality and prejudice in our own society, to perpetuating it? Are the elite planting seeds in our newest generation that will prolong this nightmare of pornographic manipulation?          After being exposed to Williams, one gets a sense that she isn't radical; she is awakening us to the inherent hypocrisy of a nation where all "men are created equal" yet some men are treated less humanly. She is a voice of educated protest. She is a passionate, angry voice that stirs up social consciences and awareness of our own role in the perpetuation of societal boundaries. Despite language ranging from the intensely personal to the admittedly irrational, her credibility remains intact because her work demands that we take her on as a person, not as a cheap characterization like the Nutty Black Feminst Ultra-Liberal Professor. The key to accessing Williams is the key she teaches us for accessing a more equal society: a society in which pigeon holes are eliminated, since clearly, neither we nor Patricia Williams can be so categorized without losing our humanity. Davis                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                               Return to Mercer Street 2001 Table of Contents          by Jordan Davis                   While most pundits of America's social and political discourse are either beating dead horses or tilting at windmills, Patricia J. Williams seeks out the racist, sexist, heterosexist, and classist forces that underlie a number of socio-political pathologies. Williams' regular Nation magazine column, "Diary of a Mad Law Professor" is curious in that it often evokes visceral negativity in casual readers. It certainly affected me that way. At first it was difficult to get beyond the name of her page; thumbing through each issue I sheepishly wondered what this crazy lady would get bent out of shape about this week. Though I generally agreed with her ideas, it struck me that Williams was too radical (as if there really is such a thing in a mainstream media culture that chooses to wear blinders). Williams vigorously uproots conventional wisdom as she strips away the "rich-white-male"-centric viewpoint; power and a voice are given to those who simply are acted upon. Like Howard Zinn who has promoted a view of history through a populist lens, Patricia Williams promotes a viewpoint that examines and judges the treatment of the marginalized.          Williams is clearly not the only contemporary essayist with a broad-minded viewpoint on social issues. Katha Pollitt, E.L. Doctorow, Gore Vidal, and Alexander Cockburn, among many others, are similarly progressive in their opinions on society, politics, and culture. Williams, however, has a modified gestalt upon which her liberal commentary about socio-political affairs is based. The way in which the mechanics of society can be explained is a relationship of dominance and submission, a pornographic association. As described in "Clarence X", pornography, on a level greater than graphic sexuality, is "a habit of thinking that allows self-generated sensation to substitute for interaction with a whole other human being, to substitute for listening or conversing or caring." (123). That which becomes such an object, be it an entire race, class, or identifiable group is transformed into a "malleable 'thing'" upon which to project (123). Pornography's purpose is a blank screen upon which the voyeur's desires are projected; a blank screen upon which "the object becomes interchangeable with the will of the voyeur" (123).          Furthermore, pornography has a clear delineation between those who act and those who are acted upon. In this dichotomy of the active and the passive, dominance and submission are key to serving pornography's purpose. In society the roles of voyeur and "actor" are superimposed: thus dominant groups in society project whatever fears and desires they have onto submissive (read: repressed) groups. To demonstrate such patterns, Williams often exposes what is unconscious and what is taboo-that which we either are unaware of and that which sits in the room like a giant white (black?) elephant that we all try to ignore. Unconscious characterizations of groups become tools upon which the justification of their plight is constructed.          Williams' "Fire and Ice," published in The Alchemy of Race and Rights , explores the tensions (and projections) between the existing and new residents of neighborhoods undergoing gentrification. Manhattan's Noho area during the early 1990s was undergoing social and economic change. As streets like Lafayette and the Bowery had once been refuges for the homeless, their downtown location became desirable for the significantly more affluent. Williams recounts a "neurotic New Yorker" asking her to call the police because, "There are BUMS in the lobby [of her building] again" (134). When Williams explained that she would not call the police on "one old, bent toothless black woman huddled under a yellow blanket with holes in it," the woman became irate, claiming that she was spending "too much goddamned money" to have to deal with those "dangerous" people (134-135). Was an "old, bent toothless black woman" truly "dangerous," or was this a reflex? Certainly, it must be inconvenient to be reminded of one's own role in the plight of America's social underclass through the capitalistic indulgence of gentrification. Economic losers are demonized, and the irrational fear of the homeless perpetuates their plight.          Similarly, negative stereotypes of blacks become intertwined with latent perceptions of ownership, thus reinforcing the racial splintering of New York City. A major example of this thinking is explained in "Teleology on the Rocks." In the wake of the Howard Beach beatings, in which three white teenagers assaulted a group of black men whose car had broken down, Mayor Koch went to the largely black neighborhood of Jamaica to explain the "disgruntlement of residents of Howard Beach" in reference to the interracial protest march that followed the beatings (69). Koch asking them "how they would feel if fourteen hundred white people took to their streets of Jamaica" belies the acceptance of "a remarkable degree of possessiveness about public streets. . .that is racially and not geographically bounded" (69). This ill-fated peace mission by the mayor exposed the attitudes that contribute to a de facto segregation of the City of New York. This undercurrent of supposed racial boundaries was taken advantage of by defense attorneys who claimed that the black men who were walking through the white Howard Beach neighborhood should have stopped at the first available pay phone to get help-they had no business walking into the neighborhood in the first place. The increasing number of affluent whites moving into Harlem, as documented in "Little House in the 'Hood," shows the double standard pertaining to whites moving into traditionally black neighborhoods. Whites are at leisure to move into black neighborhoods, pushing out less affluent minorities-the stable residents that have maintained and fought for improvements in their neighborhood as in Harlem. Howard Beach was a good neighborhood threatened by bad elements; Harlem is a "bad" neighborhood "crying out" for a savior.          Inherent in the relationship of whites and blacks in Howard Beach and Harlem is a projection of stereotypes that serve to polarize "good" and "bad" in the eyes of whites. Blacks are viewed in their stereotypically pathological lifestyles. Why do such feelings exist? Whites project these feelings, these underlying tensions and stereotypes, to make themselves feel more secure. They "know" who the "enemy" is so whenever black men wander into a neighborhood for "no good reason," an appropriate and clear response can immediately be summoned; "those blacks" only bring no good. Whites "know" that the minority neighborhoods they decide to take over are "ghettos" rampant with the dysfunctional black culture of drugs, violence, and broken families. Like European explorers "discovering" the Americas and Africa, these whites view themselves as the tamers of neighborhoods blighted by the poor and lazy, and otherwise inferior. Blacks are thus painted with a broad brush; they become objects of fear and loathing. Stepping away from the distorted lens of such racial pornography, it appears that white fears are indeed hypocritical.          White, straight, Protestant male America's individual phobias are given a collective voice, however, thanks to the media's lens which renders images as accurately as a fun-house mirror. The media's very nature takes public views and crams them into private spaces, be it the television in the living room, the stereo in a taxi, or the tabloid headline screaming from a newsstand. Its influence lies in its universality. Individual fears (dangerous homeless people, violent black men, etc.) are cultivated, harvested, and sold wholesale in a perverted marketplace of ideas. Here the media portrays what dominant societal groups want to see: marginalized groups that embody and affirm their ambitions, their ignorance and their worst fears. Like sexual pornography in which roles of dominance and submission are recreated in visual portrayals and manifestly in real life, this media pornography relays stereotypes that become self-fulfilling prophecies in the physical world. Williams' deconstruction of these forces is done by her appropriation of their own techniques. There is a clear impression of how the media, crackpot and mainstream, maintain and propagate inequality.          Conservative talk radio is certifiably the one media outlet where ill-informed babble is purposefully aimed at projecting fears onto people that become "their property." In "Radio Hoods," Williams characteristically dissects the banter of the AM spectrum by serving up the rhetoric in a bare-bones, slightly-irrational approach, all the while embracing the kernel of absurdity she is cracking: "Is it really just a collapsing economy that spawns this drama of grown people sitting around scaring themselves to death with fantasies of black feminist Mexican able-bodied gay soldiers earning $100,000 a year on welfare who are so criminally depraved. . .?" (47). Williams neatly rolls up many subjects (victims) of hate radio into a neat package that both names victims and at the same time displays stereotypes. In the white, Protestant, straight male world of talk radio, any members of society not in this narrow category are seen as the victimizers of the allegedly endangered white male race. Talk show hosts, with their-quoting the National Review on (King) Rush Limbaugh-"splendidly awful taste" and "delightful offensiveness," use "coded epithets" against the supposed enemy (47, 44). Because the very "megawatted expressions of hate and discrimination" are so nakedly aimed at degradation, Williams does not need to do any doctoring whatsoever. The targets of these rants, onto whom the blame for everything under the sun is pinned, are referred to, in their own words, as "'these people', or 'these minorities' or 'feminazis' or 'liberals' or 'scumbags' or 'pansies' or 'jerks' or 'sleazeballs' or 'loonies' or 'animals' or 'foreigners'" (44). These scapegoats are turned into the property of the listener through degrading labels that wrap these "undesirables" up into a tight package to be batted about at will. Williams also faults the hosts who through "mockery and shouting down of callers. . .roar[s] of incantations, [and] the insistence on agreement," foster culture in which the dominant group is still able to categorize, and thus, dehumanize their supposed enemies (47).          Culture, politics, and the media join together in vivid, pornographic interplay in Williams' "Clarence X" in The Rooster's Egg . In describing the one aspect of pornography associated with controversial Supreme Court Justice Clarence Thomas, Williams uses an extended comparison. She compares Clarence Thomas to Wanda the Wench-comparing an icon of pornographized white racist desires to pornographized male sexual desires. Like female objects in sexual pornography who "enjoy" their dehumanization, Thomas is characterized as "lov[ing] the good old days when a little oppression was good for the soul. . .and taught him the true meaning of community" (124). She finishes with a line whose double entendre is stark: "Affirmative action just emasculates him, and besides blacks should be free to experience the self-help joys of a little bondage" (124). The painful gravity and dark humor of this statement reflects no doubt the irony of a black man who is more conservative on social issues than many conservative white judges. It furthermore paints a subtle picture of an Uncle Tom, perhaps the most pornographized image of American slavery.          Such stark examples will likely be assailed by critics as melodramatic and convoluted, but they drive home the point that Thomas, one of the few blacks in the judiciary with conservative views on par with Justice Scalia, is a symbol of the black man who refuses to step on white peoples' toes. Williams shows that Thomas' attraction was his image as a man who sees nothing wrong with the current state of social and economic inequality: Thomas fit into conservative white desires of a black man who wouldn't speak out, an Uncle Tom or a Mammy. The mainstream press would generally shun such powerful, stinging images, yet this is the essence of Williams' unique wake-up call. Here the underlying cynical racism, in which Thomas plays a role, is unearthed from beneath the heap of political image-making charades by Williams' incisive irreverence.          Comparing Thomas to "Wanda," Williams shows him to be a pacified individual who is rendered malleable by image experts in order to mass-market him. Neo-conservative Justice Thomas was once quoted as calling the 60's Black Nationalist Malcolm X one of his role models. Williams doesn't miss a step in "Clarence X": "Clarence Thomas is to Malcolm X what 'Unforgettable. The perfume. By Revlon' Is to Nat King Cole" (125). This comparison of the sublime and the ridiculous shadows the absurdity of image-making. The humor of such a typical reprimand is tempered by the fact that many blacks did indeed support him. Thomas' mythology was "helpfully concocted by some of the very same public relations people" who marketed George Bush, Ross Perot, Jesse Helms, and Ronald Reagan (125). Williams' scathing criticism of Justice Thomas and his portrayal in the easily-manipulated media was peppered with cutting allusions (in this particular case, an allusion to Ntozake Shange's For Colored Girls Who Have Considered Suicide/When the Rainbow is Enuf ) and readily accessible images. One such example: Justice Thomas was represented "as the product of a land where odds are always overcome, where workers whistle, and where the rainbow is enuf" (126). This marketing of a conservative Thomas as a blend of "Horatio Alger, Miss Jane Pittman and Colin Powell" easily manipulated those in a culture where the media has derelicted its post as watchdog (126). The media allowed itself to be a sort of Wanda the Wench, a body at the service of whatever dominating forces desire it.          With the media acting as a passive Wanda, an intelligent black woman, who intended to make waves and refused to be pacified, was relentlessly attacked for daring to break the boundaries of what others thought she should be. In "A Hearing of One's Own," Williams depicts the ill-fated nomination of Lani Guinier where "she was successfully represented as someone who hated whites and all of Western civilization" (138-139). This was despite the very fact that Guinier is herself the child of an interracial marriage and the third generation of a family of lawyers (138). Guinier was depersonalized; media coverage was not about what she said, but about what she was supposed to have said. There was the "ubiquitous image of Guinier-lips moving, voiceover confirming your worst fears about what she was supposed to have written, what she was supposed to be" (144).          Guinier was branded with the mantle of the "radical black woman," not unlike the outspoken Patricia Williams herself. Because she was not the "typical" black woman riddled with social pathology, she was depicted as "black nationalist" and "irrational feminist" all rolled into one. Society's media has dictated, as was evidenced in the victim bashing during the Tawana Brawley rape trial, that "black women whore as a way of being . . . because it is sensual and lazy and vengeful. How can one be raped?" ("Mirrors and Windows" 175). Furthermore, black women are supposed to be "the bad black mother" ("The Pain of Word Bondage" 163). While blackness invites a series of lurid emotional expectations, being female demands a certain passiveness, like Wanda. Being assertive, intelligent, and persistent draws images of "bitchy, lesbian feminazis," and women who dare to step out of their place, making themselves other than an object for men, draw intense revulsion. The media portrayal and the consequent negative public opinion of Hillary Clinton demonstrated the wrath that punishes a woman daring to abandon her apron for a pantsuit. Lani Guinier thus suffered the double weight of being both a woman and black in the white-male media spotlight.          Consequently, Williams never mentions what Guinier actually said because the entire question of what she really said is moot in light of the fact that she is condemned to history books with words stuck in her mouth by white men who need her to be the irrational, ultra-liberal black woman. She had to wear the crown of thorns as "Quota Queen" ("A Hearing of One's Own, 144-146). Williams' treatment of the "Quota Queen" thus parallels the way in which she was handled by the press. There are abundant quotes from others about what she supposedly said, and there are comparisons of Guinier to the highly-controversial Leonard Jeffries and other Right-wing archetypes of "neo-liberalism," yet there is no discussion or even explanation of her as a person. Though Williams investigates the treatment of Guinier and the underlying motives, Guinier's own ideas are never expressed. Her "supposed" opinions robbed her of a hearing and any possibility of her actually speaking for herself and contradicting the media's anti-Guinier propaganda. Williams herself takes on the role as pornographer for a chapter in order to subtly highlight the workings of Guinier's intellectual rape and her political dehumanization; Guinier just appears as a crazy black lady talking nonsense.          The archetype of the uneducated black person was again echoed in Episode I: The Phantom Menace . One such character, Jar Jar Binks, who speaks "coincidentally" with a Caribbean/West African accent closely associated with African-Americans, is played as "loping", "popeyed", and "brainless" ("Racial Ventriloquism" 9). In the aptly titled "Racial Ventriloquism," Williams criticizes the Amos n'Andy-like portrayals of negative blacks, as well as images that perpetuate the stereotypes of Jews as money-grubbing and soulless. This is perhaps an example of racial pornography at its worst: the creation of fictional characters-aliens-embodying negative stereotypes of today. Williams draws extensively upon the blatant characterizations in both the film and Star Wars Episode I: The Visual Dictionary , and clearly, these characterizations fit into a larger pattern of stereotypes that dehumanize. Is this film, with a large following by children, part of the maintenance of racist institutional thought? Does this film cross the line from a mirror of the inequality and prejudice in our own society, to perpetuating it? Are the elite planting seeds in our newest generation that will prolong this nightmare of pornographic manipulation?          After being exposed to Williams, one gets a sense that she isn't radical; she is awakening us to the inherent hypocrisy of a nation where all "men are created equal" yet some men are treated less humanly. She is a voice of educated protest. She is a passionate, angry voice that stirs up social consciences and awareness of our own role in the perpetuation of societal boundaries. Despite language ranging from the intensely personal to the admittedly irrational, her credibility remains intact because her work demands that we take her on as a person, not as a cheap characterization like the Nutty Black Feminst Ultra-Liberal Professor. The key to accessing Williams is the key she teaches us for accessing a more equal society: a society in which pigeon holes are eliminated, since clearly, neither we nor Patricia Williams can be so categorized without losing our humanity.
